<article id=3D"content" role=3D"main">

<!-- #BeginEditable "Body" -->=20


<h1 class=3D"center">Heron's Formula</h1>=20


<p style=3D"float:left; margin: 0 10px 5px 0;"><img src=3D"https://www.math=
sisfun.com/geometry/images/triangle-eq-sss.svg" alt=3D"triangle sss" height=
=3D"134" width=3D"133"></p>=20


<h2>Area of a Triangle from Sides</h2>=20

<p>We can calculate the area of a triangle if we know the lengths of all th=
ree sides, using a formula that has been known for nearly 2000 years.</p>=
=20
<p>It is called "Heron's Formula" after Hero of Alexandria (see below)</p>=
=20
<p>&nbsp;</p>=20
<p>We use this two step process:</p>=20
<p><b>Step 1:</b> Calculate <b>"s"</b> (half of the triangles perimeter):</=
p>=20
<p class=3D"center large">s =3D <span class=3D"intbl"><em>a+b+c</em><strong=
>2</strong></span></p>=20
<p><b>Step 2:</b> Then calculate the <b>Area</b>:</p>=20
<div class=3D"center large">A =3D <span style=3D"font-size:120%;">=E2=88=9A=
</span><span class=3D"overline">s(s=E2=88=92a)(s=E2=88=92b)(s=E2=88=92c)</s=
pan></div><!-- A =3D SQR(s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)) --><br>


<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: What is the area of a triangle where every side is 5 long?</h=
3>=20

	<p>Step 1: s =3D <span class=3D"intbl"><em>5+5+5</em><strong>2</strong></s=
pan> =3D 7,5</p>=20
	<p>Step 2: A =3D =E2=88=9A(7,5 =C3=97 2,5 =C3=97 2,5 =C3=97 2,5) =3D =E2=
=88=9A(117,1875) =3D <b>10,825...</b></p>=20
	</div>
<p>Try it yourself:</p>=20

<iframe width=3D"100%" height=3D"283px" scrolling=3D"no" title=3D"JavaScrip=
t Animation" style=3D"display: block; margin: auto; border: none; backgroun=
d-color: transparent; overflow: hidden; transition: 0.6s ease-in-out; max-w=
idth: 100%;"></iframe><div class=3D"script" style=3D"height: 360px; display=
: none;"> images/heron.js</div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>=20
<div class=3D"sidebar">=20
<p style=3D"float:left; margin: 0 10px 5px 0;"><img src=3D"https://www.math=
sisfun.com/geometry/images/hero-of-alexandria.jpg" alt=3D"xAS" height=3D"18=
0" width=3D"150"></p>=20

<h3>Hero of Alexandria</h3>=20

<p>The formula is credited to Hero (or Heron) of Alexandria, who was a Gree=
k Engineer and Mathematician   in 10 =E2=80=93 70 AD.</p>=20
<p>Amongst other things, he developed the <b><i>Aeolipile</i></b>, the  fir=
st known steam engine, but it was treated as a toy!</p>=20
</div>=20


<h2>Angles</h2>=20

<p>In the calculator above I  also used the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisf=
un.com/algebra/trig-cosine-law.html">Law of Cosines</a> to calculate the an=
gles (for a complete solution). The formula is:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/images/=
triangle-angle-from-sides.png" alt=3D"triangle angle from sides C =3D cos^-=
1( (a^2+b^2-c^2)/2ab )" height=3D"47" width=3D"210"></p>=20
<p>Where "C" is the  angle <b>opposite</b> side "c".</p>=20
<p>&nbsp;</p>=20
